{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527203"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:29:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14192"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14192"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.24,0.02,0.07,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114344"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6875"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14192"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96344"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4918"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11471"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45584"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46707"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114344"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with concerns about his social interactions and communication difficulties. He reports longstanding challenges in maintaining friendships, understanding social cues, and adapting to changes in routine. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He maintains minimal eye contact during the consultation and speaks in a monotonous voice. He also mentions occasional episodes of \u0027zoning out\u0027 and that his father\u0027s brother has intellectual disability. Recent blood tests show slightly elevated TSH levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in investigating this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Electroencephalogram (EEG)","Full blood count and thyroid function tests","Brain MRI","Genetic testing for Fragile X syndrome","Referral for Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule (ADOS-2) assessment"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of autism spectrum disorder (ASD), including longstanding social communication difficulties, challenges with social cues, and restricted behaviours. The most appropriate next step is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereferral for Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule (ADOS-2) assessment\u003C/strong\u003E. The ADOS-2 is the gold standard observational assessment tool for diagnosing ASD in adults, involving semi-structured assessment of communication, social interaction, and restricted and repetitive behaviours as part of a comprehensive multidisciplinary evaluation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic testing for Fragile X syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely recommended for diagnosing ASD in adults unless there are specific indications including characteristic physical features. Fragile X syndrome follows X-linked inheritance, meaning the gene is located on the X chromosome. Since males inherit their X chromosome from their mother and Y chromosome from their father, father-to-son transmission of X-linked conditions is impossible. In this example, the family history of intellectual disability in the paternal uncle does not suggest Fragile X syndrome risk for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain MRI\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eelectroencephalogram (EEG)\u003C/strong\u003E are not routine investigations for suspected ASD in adults unless there are additional neurological symptoms suggesting other underlying conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood count and thyroid function tests\u003C/strong\u003E are not specific investigations for ASD and do not contribute directly to the diagnosis, despite the elevated TSH noted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) diagnosis in adults requires a comprehensive multidisciplinary assessment, including detailed developmental history and standardised diagnostic tools.","The Autism Diagnostic Observation Schedule (ADOS-2) is a gold standard observational assessment for diagnosing ASD in adults.","Fragile X syndrome follows X-linked inheritance, making father-to-son transmission impossible."],"references":["American Psychiatric Association DS, American Psychiatric Association DS. Diagnostic and statistical manual of mental disorders: DSM-5. Washington, DC: American psychiatric association; 2013 May 22."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96344"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14192"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96344"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T18:20:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T18:21:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6875"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114344"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde